\subsubsection{Distance-Dependent Correlation $C(d)$}
The distance-band mean correlations (aggregated over all ${{.NumDims}}$ basis dimensions) are:

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{|l|r|}
\hline
\textbf{Distance Band} & \textbf{Mean $C(d)$} \\ \hline
{{range .Bands}}$d \in [{{.Dmin}},{{.Dmax}}]$ & ${{.Mean | signed}}$ \\ \hline
{{end}}\end{tabular}
\caption{Mean phase correlation $C(d)$ by distance band. The sign transition from negative
(short-range repulsion) to positive (medium/long-range attraction) at $d\approx{{.ZeroCrossing}}$
defines the characteristic phase correlation length of the basis prime encoding.}
\end{table}

The zero crossing at $d\approx{{.ZeroCrossing}}$ is the characteristic phase correlation length
of the encoding. Contiguous splits preserve this repulsive-to-attractive transition, giving each
block a distinctive internal ``phase texture.'' Random splits homogenise distances, destroying
this texture.

